What is the significance of the written number "三百八" in Chinese culture and why has it been used for so many years instead of Arabic numerals?</s> 
In traditional Chinese, written numbers were used to represent large numbers. In ancient times, Chinese people used their fingers to count and used the thumb as the first finger to represent the digit 1, then they used the index finger for digit 2, middle finger for digit 3, and ring finger for digit 4. This system of counting led to the use of written numbers to represent large numbers.

The number "三百八" (300 + 8) can be traced back to the Qin dynasty (221 BCE-206 BCE) and has been used for more than 2,000 years. It was used to represent a large number of people or things, and it was believed to have special connotations such as prosperity, good luck, and longevity. The number "三百八" is still used today to express the meaning of "abundant" in Chinese culture.
